solution.p:
Using the formula for the operation of an ideal constant volume gas thermometer we find the temperature in the Absolute scale to be

	 T \amp = \frac{p}{p_\text{TP}} T_\text{TP} 
	 \amp = \frac{1100\text{ Pa}}{1500\text{ Pa}}\times 273.16\text{K} = 200.32\text{K}.

We look up a table of data for the triple point of nitrogen gas, which is listed at -210.1^{\circ}\text{C}.  In the kelvin scale the temperature is 273.15-210.10 = 63.05\text{K}. Now, using the formula for the operation of an ideal constant volume gas thermometer we find the pressure:

	 p \amp = \frac{T}{T_\text{TP}} p_\text{TP} 
	 \amp = \frac{(273.15+30)\text{K}}{63.05\text{K}}\times 2000\textrm{ Pa} = 9616\text{ Pa}.
